(10. I should use argument groups in Python's argparse module more than I do) Tj
T*
(Source: Chris's Wiki :: blog | Published: 2026-04-02T02:44:10Z) Tj
T*
(Link: https://utcc.utoronto.ca/~cks/space/blog/python/ArgparseOptionGroupsPraise) Tj
T*
(For reasons well outside the scope of this entry, the other day I looked at the --help output) Tj
T*
(from one of my old Python programs. This particular program has a lot of options, but when I'd) Tj
T*
(written it, I had used argparse argument groups to break up the large list of options into) Tj
T*
(logical groups, starting with the most important and running down to the 'you should probably) Tj
T*
(ignore these' ones. The result was far more readable than it would have been without the) Tj
T*
(grouping. \(I want to call these 'option groups', because that's what I use them for.\) I've) Tj
T*
(regularly used mutual exclusion groups in my recent Python programs, but for some reason I've) Tj
T*
(fallen so much out of the habit of using argparse groups to break up walls of options that I'd) Tj
T*
(forgot they even existed until I was reminded by my own program's --help output. Now that I've) Tj
T*
(been reminded, there are probably some programs that I should go back to and add some groups) Tj
T*
(to. \(Most or all of my programs with a lot of options have a structure to them; it's not just a) Tj
T*
(kitchen sink of a lot of things. Even if there is no real structure I can at least separate) Tj
T*
(things into frequent, less frequent, and obscure options.\) Although you can't pu...) Tj
T*
() Tj
